60–1304","1196–1259":"1196–1259","1196–Female":"1196–Deceased","1242":"1242","1220":"1220","1196":"1196","1284":"1284","1260":"1260","1290":"1290","after 1302":"after 1302","1304":"1304","1259":"1259","1226":"1226","1302":"1302","1234":"1234","1222":"1222","1276":"1276","16 March 1284":"16 March 1284","1306":"1306","Longford, Derbyshire, England":"Longford, Derbyshire, England","Horbury, Yorkshire, England":"Horbury, Yorkshire, England","Horbury, Wakefield, Yorkshire, England":"Horbury, Yorkshire, England","Gwynedd, Wales, United Kingdom":"Gwynedd, Wales, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Horbury","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English: locative name from Horbury in Wakefield (WR Yorks)."],"variants":[{"name":"Aubrey","meanings":["English: from the Middle English male personal name <i>Albry</i>, <i>Aubry</i>, or <i>Aubery</i>, a borrowing of Old French <i>Alberi</i>, <i>Aubri</i> (from ancient Germanic <i>Alberic</i>, which is composed of the elements <i>alb</i> ‘elf’ and <i>ric</i> ‘powerful’).","English: from the Middle English female personal name <i>Albrey</i>, <i>Aubrey</i>, a borrowing from Old French <i>Albree</i>, <i>Aubree</i>, <i>Auberee</i> (from ancient Germanic <i>Albrad(a)</i>).","English: variant of <b>Abery</b>, a habitational name from a local pronunciation of Avebury, Wiltshire. The placename derives from Old English <i>burh</i> ‘stronghold, fortified place’, with an uncertain first element, possibly the Old English personal name <i>Afa</i>."]},{"name":"Holberry","meanings":["English: variant of   Horbury  ; see   Redmonds, Dictionary of Yorks Surnames  ."]},{"name":"Horberry","meanings":["English: variant spelling of   Horbury   or   Aubrey  ."]}]},{"name":"Agnes","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Latinized version of the Greek name <i>Hagnē</i>, from the feminine form of the adjective <i>hagnos</i> ‘pure, holy’. This was the name of a young Roman virgin martyred in the persecutions instigated by the Roman emperor Diocletian in   ad  303 . She became a very popular saint in the Middle Ages. Her name was early associated with Latin <i>agnus</i> ‘lamb’, leading to the consistent dropping of the initial <i>H-</i> and to her representation in art accompanied by a lamb. The colloquial form <i>Annes</i> led to some confusion with <i>Ann(e)</i> in earlier centuries. Frequent in the medieval period, the name was revived in the 19th century, and has been especially popular in Scotland.  See also  Annis ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705189,"age":17,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705190,"age":48,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"W